<dl id="n36207k"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n36" href="#n36207k">N36 (VI.B.29)</a>:  <a href="../../FF/fnbs/n36all.htm#n36207k"> 207(k)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> Yaughurda</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources"><font color="green">[The Swamis and Yogis.]</font> It remained, however, for the ineffable Swami <mark>Yoganda</mark> to sell Hindu philosophy to Americans by American methods. &hellip; The first Yogoda Sat-Sanga Centre was organised in Boston. &hellip; Yogoda means in plain American a system which &ldquo;teaches are to harmonise all the faculties and forces that operate for the perfection of mind, body, and soul&rdquo;. Sat-Sanga means &ldquo;fellowship with Truth&rdquo;. <small> Charles W. Ferguson, <a name="CFCT" href="../../FF/fdra/fdex.htm#CFCT"><cite title="source">The Confusion of Tongues</cite></a> (1928; rpt. May 1929) 312</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
